  "source_url": "https://oracc.museum.upenn.edu/etcsri/Q001934",
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "para_id": "Q001934.1",
      "line_range": "1",
      "translation": "(1) When Šu-ilišu , the powerful man , king of Urim , brought home ( the statue of ) Nanna from Anšan to Urim , then for Nanna , the most outstanding among the Anuna gods , his master , he built the Dublamah , his place of rendering judgement . He installed for him a decorated two-wing door , and dedicated it to him for his well-being ."
    },
    {
      "para_id": "Q001934.19",
      "line_range": "19",
      "translation": "(19) Whoever gives order to perform a misdeed against this ( door ) , transfers it to a storehouse , or makes another man raise his hand against it on account of this curse , may Nanna , my master , and Ningal , my lady , curse him !"
    }
  ],
